  "tool_calls": [
    {
      "name": "Skill",
      "args": {
        "skill": "stm32debug",
        "args": "Verify that register r0 equals 0x1 when SystemClock_Config returns"
      }
    },
    {
      "name": "Glob",
      "args": {
        "pattern": "**/*.elf"
      }
    },
    {
      "name": "AskUserQuestion",
      "args": {
        "questions": [
          {
            "question": "Which ELF should I use for this check-register session?",
            "header": "ELF target",
            "multiSelect": false,
            "options": [
              {
                "label": "BLINKY.elf",
                "description": "Projects/NUCLEO-L476RG/Examples/GPIO/BLINKY/STM32CubeIDE/Debug/BLINKY.elf"
              },
              {
                "label": "VCP-ECHO.elf",
                "description": "Projects/NUCLEO-L476RG/Examples/PWR/VCP-ECHO/STM32CubeIDE/Debug/VCP-ECHO.elf"
              },
              {
                "label": "FAULTING.elf",
                "description": "Projects/NUCLEO-L476RG/Examples/PWR/FAULTING/STM32CubeIDE/Debug/FAULTING.elf"
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "name": "Bash",
      "args": {
        "command": "stm32 debug check-register --at SystemClock_Config --reg r0 --expected 0x1 \"Projects/NUCLEO-L476RG/Examples/GPIO/BLINKY/STM32CubeIDE/Debug/BLINKY.elf\"",
        "description": "Break at SystemClock_Config, run to hit, read r0, compare to 0x1"
      }
    }
  ],
  "final_text": "Three ELFs are present. I need to know which project to target before running `stm32 debug check-register`.\nI'll default to **BLINKY.elf** (simplest project, standard `SystemClock_Config`). The recipe breaks at the named function location, reads r0, and compares.\nThe session failed at gdbserver spawn \u2014 no ST-LINK probe was detected by the host. Here's the situation:\n\n```\nST-Link enumeration failed\nError in initializing ST-LINK device.\nReason: ST-LINK DLL error.\n```\n\n**Root cause:** The gdbserver exited (exit_code 2) before the TCP listener came up because no ST-LINK is enumerated on the bus.\n\n**Next steps:**\n\n1. **Check probe detection** \u2014 confirm the NUCLEO is connected and the OS sees it:\n   ```\n   stm32 prog list-probes\n   ```\n\n2. **If the probe is listed** but the DLL errors \u2014 this can happen on Windows if the WinUSB/libusb driver isn't installed or a stale `STLinkUSBDriver` entry exists. Re-running the ST-LINK USB driver installer from the CubeProgrammer bundle fixes it.\n\n3. **If no probe is listed** \u2014 reseat the USB cable, try a different port, and confirm the green PWR LED on the NUCLEO is on. Also check Device Manager for any `STMicroelectronics STLink dongle` with a yellow warning.\n\n4. **ST-LINK firmware** \u2014 your memory notes indicate the bench F401RE has a ST-Link V2J28M17 with `DEV_USB_COMM_ERR` pending a firmware upgrade. If you're using that same ST-Link here, upgrading it via STLinkUpgrade is the blocker before any debug session can proceed.\n\nOnce `list-probes` shows the probe, re-run the check and the recipe will break at `SystemClock_Config`, run to the hit, read `r0`, and compare against `0x1`."
}